            "id": "c1a0b414b1dd4c2783f3f",
            "questionText": "An electron with a charge $!$q = -1.6 \\times 10^{-19} C$!$ and mass $!$m = 9.11 \\times 10^{-31} kg$!$ is shot horizontally with an initial velocity of $!$u = 3 \\times 10^6 m/s$!$ into a uniform electric field between two parallel plates. The electric field strength is $!$E = 200 N/C$!$. After traveling a horizontal distance of $!$x = 0.1 m$!$ through the field, what is the change in the electron's kinetic energy $!$\\Delta E_k$!$ due to its vertical acceleration?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "d1e04283f8f0420490ea4",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the electron's vertical acceleration. Identify the correct formula that relates the electric field, charge, and mass to the acceleration.",
